{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> γᾰλήν-η</b>, ἡ, <br /> <b>stillness of the sea, calm</b> (γ. μὲν ἐν θαλάσσῃ νηνεμία δ᾽ ἐν ἀέρι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Topica” 108b25, but compare 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 5.452, 12.168), 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus only in 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey”, λευκ ὴ δ᾽ ἦν ἀμφὶ γαλήνη 10.94 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; οἱ δ᾽ ἐλόωσι γαλήνην will sail the <b>calm sea</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7.319 \">Refs</a>]; <b>stillness</b> of deep waters, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.AD: Coluthus Epicus 360; νηνεμίας τε καὶ γ. 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Theaetetus” 153c; ἐν ταῖς γ. καὶ εὐδίαις 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Historia Animalium” 533b30 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>metaphorically</i> of the mind, <b>calmness, serenity</b>, φρόνημα νηνέμου γαλάνας [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 740 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; ἐν γαλήνῃ in <b>calm, quiet</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 899; γ. ἐν τῇ ψυχῇ 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 791a. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>lead sulphide, galena</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.AD: Plinius Rerum Naturalium Scriptor “Historia Naturalis” 33.95, 34.159. \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> name of an <b>antidote</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.AD: Andromachus Poeta Medicus cited in 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 14.32. (_Aeolic dialect_ γελήνη (sic)\">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>] <i>accusative</i> to [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"6th c.AD: Joannes Alexandrinus Grammaticus “Comp.” 3.1\">Refs 6th c.AD+</a>]; perhaps akin to γελάω.)","strongNumber":"G1055","accentedUnicode":"γαλήνη","shortDef":"calm","mediumDef":"<b>tranquillity of the sea, a calm,</b> <ref='Mat.8.26'>Mt. 8:26</ref>; <re